548","1563":"1563","1530":"1530","1518":"1518","1515":"1515","Ballyshannon, Donegal, Ireland":"Ballyshannon, County Donegal, Irland","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England","Scotland":"Skotland","Norfolk,England":"Norfolk, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1542–1566":"1542–1566","1530–1600":"1530–1600","1563–1620":"1563–1620","1515–1566":"1515–1566","1518–Female":"1518–Overleden","1547":"1547","1600":"1600","1566":"1566","1620":"1620","1542":"1542","about 1548":"circa 1548","1563":"1563","1530":"1530","1518":"1518","1515":"1515","Ballyshannon, Donegal, Ireland":"Ballyshannon, County Donegal, Ierland","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England","Scotland":"Schotland","Norfolk,England":"Norfolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1542–1566":"1542–1566","1530–1600":"1530–1600","1563–1620":"1563–1620","1515–1566":"1515–1566","1518–Female":"1518–Deceased","1547":"1547","1600":"1600","1566":"1566","1620":"1620","1542":"1542","about 1548":"about 1548","1563":"1563","1530":"1530","1518":"1518","1515":"1515","Ballyshannon, Donegal, Ireland":"Ballyshannon, County Donegal, Ireland","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England","Scotland":"Scotland","Norfolk,England":"Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"O'Donnell","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Brigid, Niall, Siobhan, Brennan, Bridie, Declan, Donal, Fergus, Jarlath, John Patrick, Padraic.","Irish (Donegal, Munster): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Domhnaill</b> ‘descendant of <i>Domhnall</i>’, an old personal name composed of the Celtic elements <i>domno-</i> ‘world’ + <i>val-</i> ‘might, rule’. Compare the Anglicized form   Donald   and the Scottish clan name   McDonald  .","History: The O'Donnells, like the O'Neills (see   O'Neill  ), claim descent from Niall of the Nine Hostages (Niall Noígíallach), a legendary 5th-century king of Ireland. Their traditional base is Tyrconnell (i.e. Donegal)."],"variants":[{"name":"O'Donell","meanings":["Irish: variant of   O'Donnell  ."]},{"name":"O'Donnel","meanings":["Irish: variant of   O'Donnell  ."]},{"name":"O'Daniel","meanings":["Irish: variant of   O'Donnell  , influenced by the Biblical name   Daniel  , to which it is etymologically unrelated."]},{"name":"O'Donald","meanings":["Irish: Scotticized form of   O'Donnell  . The Irish personal name <i>Domhnall</i> was Latinized as <i>Donaldus</i>, which is the source of <i>Donald</i>, the form of the personal name used in English in Scotland, though not in Ireland. The form <i>O'Donald</i> is therefore a 19th-century hybrid. Compare   Donald  ."]},{"name":"Donald","meanings":["Scottish: shortened form of   McDonald   (<i>Mac Dhomhnaill</i>), from the Gaelic personal name <i>Domhnall</i>; found in 13th- and 14th-century Scotland as <i>Dofnald</i>, <i>Douenald</i>, <i>Dufenald</i>, and <i>Donald</i>.","Irish (Ulster): possibly also a shortened and altered form of Irish   O'Donell  ."]}]},{"name":"Rose","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Ostensibly from the vocabulary word denoting the flower (Latin <i>rosa</i>). However, the name was in use throughout the Middle Ages, long before any of the other girls' names derived from flowers, which are generally of 19th-century origin. In part it may refer to the flower as a symbol of the Virgin Mary, but it seems more likely that it also has a Germanic origin, probably as a short form of various girls' names based on <i>hros</i> ‘horse’ or <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’. The Latinate form <i>Rohesia</i> is commonly found in documents of the Middle Ages. As well as being a name in its own right, it is currently used as a short form of   Rosemary   and, less often (because of their different pronunciation), of other names beginning <i>Ros-</i>, such as   Rosalind   and   Rosamund ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1355924,"age":5,"year":"1547","julianD